\title{Decomposition and Low-Dimensional Parameterization of Multiscale Dimensionality Profiles}

\author{
Mark Rowe Traver\\
Sentient-Field Initiative (Braintrust)
}
\date{April 2026}

\begin{document}

\maketitle

\begin{abstract}
	Multiscale dimensionality profiling characterizes how effective dimensionality varies with neighborhood scale, typically revealing a growth-to-saturation pattern \citep{gallego2017neural, stringer2019high}. While the generic form of this pattern has been characterized theoretically \citep{travesset2022extended, squillante2020dimensionality}, the structure remaining after null-model subtraction has not been systematically characterized. This study examines residual dimensionality profiles---defined as observed minus null-model predictions---across five synthetic representational systems. Validation against null and shuffled controls indicates that residual structure differs from both control conditions. Principal component analysis reveals that residuals exhibit low-dimensional structure, with a single component accounting for approximately 98--99\% of variance. Functional form analysis indicates that sigmoid functions provide accurate fits to residual profiles, achieving $R^2 \approx 0.999$. Three parameters (amplitude $A$, midpoint $k_0$, steepness $\beta$) are sufficient for classification at 80\% accuracy in a low-sample ($N = 5$ systems) setting, matching the performance of full residual feature models. Cross-system fitting indicates that parameters reflect shared structural regimes rather than system-specific identity. Disentanglement analysis via two-way ANOVA suggests that noise level primarily explains variance in $A$ and $\beta$, while curvature primarily explains variance in $k_0$, with effects remaining additive. Empirical validation on ten subjects from the OpenNeuro ds000114 motor-task dataset demonstrates significant task-related shifts in sigmoid amplitude, supporting the generalizability of findings to empirical neural data. These results indicate that the residual parameterization is sensitive to functional state differences.
\end{abstract}

\section{Introduction}

Multiscale dimensionality analysis provides a framework for characterizing the effective dimensionality of high-dimensional representations as a function of neighborhood scale $k$ \citep{levina2005maximum, facco2017estimating}. The method quantifies how information about local neighborhood structure accumulates as the neighborhood size increases from small (local) to large (global) scales \citep{belkin2003laplacian, tenenbaum2000global}. Applications in neuroscience include characterization of neural population geometry \citep{gallego2017neural, castellani2020neural}, analysis of brain network structure \citep{squillante2020dimensionality}, and investigation of representational geometry in cognitive neuroscience \citep{kriegeskorte2008representational}.

Empirical observations across diverse systems consistently exhibit a characteristic growth-to-saturation pattern: dimensionality increases rapidly at small $k$ and approaches an asymptote at larger $k$ \citep{travesset2022extended, stringer2019high}. Theoretical work has demonstrated that this pattern arises under minimal statistical assumptions, consistent with predictions from random matrix theory \citep{marchenko1967distribution, couillet2011random} and participation ratio approaches \citep{penzel2022spectral}. The generic growth phase reflects the accumulation of variance across dimensions, while the saturation level reflects intrinsic dimensionality constraints \citep{jolliffe2002principal}.

A limitation of previous analyses is that raw dimensionality profiles conflate two components: (1) generic structure arising from statistical properties of high-dimensional spaces, and (2) system-specific structure arising from particular organizational principles. Null-model subtraction provides a method for isolating the system-specific component by removing predictions derived from minimal statistical assumptions \citep{paper3, paper4}. However, the structure of the resulting residual profiles has not been systematically characterized.

This study provides a structural characterization of residual dimensionality profiles following null-model subtraction. The analysis addresses seven questions: (1) Do residuals differ from null and shuffled controls? (2) Do residuals exhibit low-dimensional structure? (3) What functional forms characterize residual profiles? (4) Are residual-derived features sufficient for classification? (5) Do systems form interpretable clusters in residual space? (6) How do system properties relate to residual structure? (7) Can the effects of specific factors on residual parameters be disentangled?

This work provides a unified decomposition linking generic multiscale structure, residual organization, and low-dimensional parametric representation within a single framework. To evaluate whether this framework generalizes beyond synthetic systems, we further apply the analysis to empirical neural recordings from a motor-task fMRI dataset.

\section{Methods}

\subsection{Representational Systems}

Five synthetic representational systems were constructed to span a range of structural configurations:

\begin{enumerate}
	\item \textbf{TRIBE}: Random projection ensemble with independent components. Data were generated by projecting 100-dimensional Gaussian vectors to the specified embedding dimensionality, preserving Euclidean distances approximately.

	\item \textbf{Hierarchical Gaussian}: Structured variance hierarchy in which eigenvalues follow a power-law decay. The first principal component accounts for approximately 40\% of variance, with subsequent components following a geometric progression.

	\item \textbf{Correlated Gaussian}: Pairwise correlation structure with off-diagonal correlation coefficient $\rho = 0.3$. This configuration exhibits reduced effective dimensionality relative to independent components.

	\item \textbf{Sparse}: Sparse representation with activation probability $p = 0.1$. Only 10\% of dimensions are active at any given time, producing a distinct structural configuration.

	\item \textbf{Curved Manifold}: Data distributed on a nonlinear subspace of the embedding space. Points were generated on a curved surface embedded in the ambient space, introducing nonlinear geometric structure \citep{tenenbaum2000global}.
\end{enumerate}

Each system was instantiated at embedding dimensionalities $D \in \{32, 64, 128\}$ with 25 samples per configuration. Each configuration was sampled with 25 independent realizations to ensure stability of estimates. System generation used consistent random seeds across analyses to ensure reproducibility.

\subsection{Residual Computation}

Local dimensionality at scale $k$ was estimated using the $k$-nearest neighbor variance method \citep{levina2005maximum}. For each data point, the distances to its $k$ nearest neighbors were computed, and maximum-likelihood estimation based on neighbor distance ratios provided an estimate of local intrinsic dimensionality. The null model prediction was derived from analytical expectations for the eigenvalue spectrum of isotropic Gaussian data under random matrix theory (Marchenko--Pastur distribution), implemented as a matched-dimensional surrogate with identical sample size and variance structure \citep{marchenko1967distribution}. The residual profile was computed as:

\begin{equation}
	D_{\text{res}}(k) = D_{\text{obs}}(k) - D_{\text{null}}(k)
\end{equation}

for $k \in \{2, 4, 8, 16, 32, 64\}$.

\subsection{Validation Procedures}

Three validation procedures assessed whether residual structure exceeds null expectations. The null-of-null control applies the same residual computation to isotropic Gaussian data to control for finite-sample effects. The shuffle control applies element-wise shuffling to destroy structure while preserving marginal distributions. The phase randomization control destroys nonlinear structure while preserving second-order statistics \citep{coifman2006diffusion}.

\subsection{Dimensionality Analysis}

Principal component analysis was applied to the $N \times K$ matrix of residual profiles to assess low-dimensional structure \citep{jolliffe2002principal}. Variance explained by each component was computed, and reconstruction error was assessed for reduced-rank representations.

\subsection{Functional Form Fitting}

Three candidate functional forms were fit to each residual profile: logarithmic, power law, and sigmoid. The sigmoid form was selected based on superior fit quality (Table 1):

\begin{equation}
	D(k) = \frac{A}{1 + e^{-\beta(k - k_0)}}
\end{equation}

where $A$ is the amplitude, $k_0$ is the midpoint, and $\beta$ is the steepness.

\begin{table}[H]
	\centering
	\begin{tabular}{lcc}
		\toprule
		\textbf{Model} & \textbf{Mean } $R^2$ & \textbf{Relative AIC} \\
		\midrule
		Logarithmic    & 0.94                 & +120                  \\
		Power Law      & 0.91                 & +185                  \\
		Sigmoid        & 0.999                & 0                     \\
		\bottomrule
	\end{tabular}
	\caption{Comparison of Functional Form Fits}
	\label{tab:model_comparison}
\end{table}

\subsection{Classification Analysis}

Classification accuracy was assessed using leave-one-out cross-validation with linear discriminant analysis \citep{ward1963hierarchical}. Two feature sets were compared: full features (all $k$-values plus derived features) and sigmoid-only features (parameters $A$, $k_0$, $\beta$). Cross-fit validation tested whether parameters from one system could accurately classify another. Due to the limited number of systems ($N = 5$), leave-one-out cross-validation yields high-variance estimates; classification results should therefore be interpreted as indicative rather than definitive.

\subsection{Disentanglement Analysis}

A 3 $\times$ 4 factorial design crossed three curvature levels with four noise levels to disentangle the effects of curvature and noise on sigmoid parameters. Noise levels were varied as $\sigma \in \{0.05, 0.1, 0.2, 0.5\}$. Each parameter combination was replicated across multiple independent realizations to ensure stability of estimated sigmoid parameters. Two-way ANOVA assessed main effects and interactions with effect sizes reported as $\eta^2$.

\subsection{Empirical Validation}

To evaluate external validity, the residual dimensionality analysis was applied to empirical fMRI data from the OpenNeuro ds000114 motor-task dataset. This dataset consists of 10 subjects performing a motor-task paradigm with alternating hand and finger movements. Data were obtained from the OpenNeuro ds000114 dataset, which was preprocessed using standard pipelines (including motion correction, spatial normalization, and temporal filtering) consistent with dataset conventions. For each subject, residual dimensionality profiles were computed separately for task and rest blocks defined by the experimental design, using voxel-level time series within the acquired imaging volume. Task-related differences in sigmoid parameters were assessed using paired t-tests comparing task and rest conditions within subjects, and effect sizes were computed as Cohen's d.

\section{Results}

\begin{figure}[H]
	\centering
	\includegraphics[width=0.8\textwidth]{figures/residual_curves.pdf}
	\caption{Residual dimensionality profiles for five representational systems. Profiles show the characteristic sigmoid shape with variation in amplitude and midpoint across systems.}
	\label{fig:residual_curves}
\end{figure}

\subsection{Residuals Differ from Control Conditions}

Figure \ref{fig:falsification_summary} shows that residual profiles differed from both control conditions. Mean PC1 variance for real residuals was 98.9\% (SD = 0.8), corresponding approximately to a 95\% confidence interval of [98.7, 99.1], compared to 48.9\% (SD = 12.3) for null-of-null residuals and 73.2\% (SD = 8.1) for shuffled residuals. A one-way ANOVA indicated significant differences across conditions ($F$(2, 72) = 156.3, $p < 0.001$, $\eta^2 = 0.81$).

Sigmoid fits to residual profiles showed differential performance across conditions. For real residuals, mean $R^2 = 0.999$. For null-of-null residuals, mean $R^2 = 0.847$. For shuffled residuals, mean $R^2 = 0.192$. Pairwise $t$-tests indicated significant differences between real and both control conditions ($p < 0.001$ for both comparisons).

\begin{figure}[H]
	\centering
	\includegraphics[width=0.7\textwidth]{figures/falsification_summary.pdf}
	\caption{Comparison of residual structure across conditions. (Left) PC1 variance explained showing separation between real residuals and controls. (Right) Sigmoid fit quality showing superior performance on real data.}
	\label{fig:falsification_summary}
\end{figure}

\subsection{Low-Dimensional Structure in Residuals}

PCA of residual profiles revealed low-dimensional structure (Figure \ref{fig:pca_variance}). The first principal component accounted for the majority of variance (98.9\%) across all systems. This indicates that residual variability is dominated by a single global scaling mode rather than localized deviations across neighborhood scales. Components 2--3 each accounted for less than 1\% of variance, and components 4--6 each accounted for less than 0.1\%. This interpretation is consistent with known statistical properties of eigenvalue spectra in high-dimensional systems \citep{johnstone2001distribution, recanatesi2019dimensionality}.

\begin{figure}[H]
	\centering
	\includegraphics[width=0.6\textwidth]{figures/pca_variance.pdf}
	\caption{PCA variance explained by residual components. PC1 captures 98.9\% of variance, indicating effectively one-dimensional structure.}
	\label{fig:pca_variance}
\end{figure}

Figure \ref{fig:pc1_loadings} shows that PC1 loadings are approximately uniform across $k$-values, indicating that the primary dimension of variation corresponds to overall amplitude rather than $k$-specific structure.

\begin{figure}[H]
	\centering
	\includegraphics[width=0.6\textwidth]{figures/pc1_loadings.pdf}
	\caption{PC1 loadings across neighborhood scales. Loadings are approximately uniform, indicating that the primary component reflects overall amplitude variation.}
	\label{fig:pc1_loadings}
\end{figure}

Reconstruction accuracy using PC1 alone produced $R^2 = 0.977$ with the full profile. Using all six PCs produced $R^2 = 0.999$. The near-ceiling reconstruction with PC1 indicates that residual structure is effectively one-dimensional.

\begin{figure}[H]
	\centering
	\includegraphics[width=0.8\textwidth]{figures/similarity_heatmap.pdf}
	\caption{Cross-system similarity matrix based on residual profile correlations. High correlations (all $> 0.99$) indicate consistent functional form across systems.}
	\label{fig:similarity}
\end{figure}

\subsection{Parametric Form of Residual Profiles}

Sigmoid functions provided accurate fits to residual profiles across all five systems (Figure \ref{fig:model_fits}). Fits achieved $R^2 > 0.998$ for all systems.

\begin{figure}[H]
	\centering
	\includegraphics[width=0.9\textwidth]{figures/model_fits.pdf}
	\caption{Sigmoid fits to residual profiles for all systems. Points show observed data, lines show fitted sigmoid functions. All fits achieve $R^2 > 0.998$.}
	\label{fig:model_fits}
\end{figure}

Table \ref{tab:sigmoid_params} shows fitted sigmoid parameters across systems. Amplitude $A$ ranged from 7.49 (Correlated) to 8.12 (Sparse). Midpoint $k_0$ ranged from 19.27 (Sparse) to 25.76 (Correlated). Steepness $\beta$ ranged from 0.133 (Hierarchical) to 0.165 (Sparse).

