\end{figure}

\subsection{Parameter Sufficiency for Classification}

Figure \ref{fig:classification} shows that classification accuracy using sigmoid-only features (three parameters) matched the accuracy achieved using full residual features. Both approaches achieved 80% classification accuracy. Given the small number of systems ($N = 5$), uncertainty is expected to be on the order of ±10%, and results should be interpreted as indicative rather than definitive.

\begin{figure}[H]
	\centering
	\includegraphics[width=0.9\textwidth]{figures/classification_results.pdf}
	\caption{Classification results. (Left) Accuracy comparison showing equivalent performance for full and sigmoid-only features. (Right) Confusion matrix for sigmoid-only classification.}
	\label{fig:classification}
\end{figure}

Feature importance analysis indicated that $\beta$ (steepness) was the most discriminative parameter (mean importance = 0.52), followed by $A$ (amplitude, importance = 0.31) and $k_0$ (midpoint, importance = 0.17).

Noise robustness testing indicated that classification accuracy remained at 80\% for noise levels up to $\sigma = 0.2$, and declined to 68\% at $\sigma = 0.5$.

\subsection{Cluster Structure}

Hierarchical clustering of sigmoid parameters produced two distinct clusters (Figure \ref{fig:dendrogram}). Cluster 1 contained the Sparse system. Cluster 0 contained all other systems (TRIBE, Hierarchical, Correlated, Curved Manifold).

Silhouette score analysis supported the two-cluster solution (mean silhouette = 0.72). Alternative solutions (3--5 clusters) produced lower silhouette scores (range: 0.41--0.58).

Cross-fit validation tested whether parameters are system-specific or shared within clusters. When parameters from one Cluster 0 system were used to classify another Cluster 0 system, accuracy remained at 80\%. When Cluster 0 parameters were used to classify Sparse (Cluster 1), accuracy dropped to 52\% (near chance for 2-class problem).

\subsection{Parameter-Property Relationships}

Parameter sweep results indicated that sigmoid parameters correlated with manipulated system properties. Noise level showed strong negative correlations with $A$ ($r = -0.97$) and $\beta$ ($r = -0.96$), and moderate positive correlation with $k_0$ ($r = 0.72$). Curvature showed strong positive correlations with all parameters ($|r| > 0.95$). Dimensionality showed moderate negative correlation with $k_0$ ($r = -0.76$).

Multiple regression with all five properties as predictors produced $R^2 = 0.89$ for the full model. Noise and curvature together accounted for $R^2 = 0.84$, indicating that these two properties explain the majority of parameter variance.

\subsection{Disentangled Factor Effects}

Two-way ANOVA revealed distinct patterns for each parameter. For amplitude $A$, noise was the dominant factor ($\eta^2 = 0.92$) with curvature explaining only 8\% of variance. For midpoint $k_0$, curvature and noise contributed comparably ($\eta^2 = 0.53$ vs 0.46). For steepness $\beta$, noise was the dominant factor ($\eta^2 = 0.58$) with curvature explaining 41\% of variance.

No significant interaction effects were observed. The curvature $\times$ noise interaction was nonsignificant for all three parameters ($p > 0.05$ for all), indicating that the effects of curvature and noise on sigmoid parameters are additive.

\subsection{Empirical Validation}

The sigmoid amplitude parameter showed a significant task-related shift relative to rest. During task blocks, the mean amplitude was $-677$ (SD = 103), compared to $-1000$ (SD = 0) during rest blocks. The absence of variance in the rest condition reflects a boundary effect of the sigmoid fitting procedure, in which amplitude estimates saturate at a lower bound under low-variance input conditions. This behavior is attributable to constrained nonlinear fitting rather than indicating an absence of underlying structure. This difference was significant ($t = 9.43$, $p < 0.0001$), corresponding to a large effect size (Cohen's d $\approx$ 2.98), though this estimate should be interpreted cautiously given the limited sample size ($N = 10$) and the boundary-constrained nature of the rest condition.
The midpoint parameter $k_0$ showed a marginally significant increase during task (task: 4.66, SD = 0.98; rest: 3.93, SD = 0.04; $t = 2.23$, $p = 0.053$). The steepness parameter $\beta$ showed a marginally significant decrease during task (task: 3.44, SD = 2.33; rest: 5.07, SD = 0.38; $t = -2.18$, $p = 0.057$).
The absence of variance in the rest amplitude condition reflects a boundary effect of the fitting procedure, in which amplitude values saturated at the lower bound across subjects. These results demonstrate that the residual dimensionality analysis framework generalizes to empirical neural data. The strong effect observed in amplitude, contrasted with marginal effects in $k_0$ and $\beta$, suggests that amplitude is the most robustly task-sensitive parameter under these conditions.

\subsection{Summary of Findings}

This study characterized the structural properties of residual dimensionality profiles following null-model subtraction. Three principal findings emerge from the analysis. In particular, this analysis extends prior findings on the generic origin and constraint limits of multiscale dimensionality profiles \citep{paper3, paper4}.

First, residual profiles exhibit low-dimensional structure. A single principal component accounts for approximately 98--99\% of variance across systems, indicating that the residual space is effectively one-dimensional. This low-dimensional structure is distinct from both null and shuffled control conditions, supporting the interpretation that residuals capture system-specific structure above null expectations \citep{levina2005maximum, jolliffe2002principal}. These observations are consistent with prior work on representational geometry and neural dimensionality, which emphasizes structured low-dimensional organization across systems \citep{kriegeskorte2013representational, cunningham2014dimensionality}.

Second, residual profiles are well-characterized by sigmoid functions. Fits achieve $R^2 > 0.998$ across all systems, substantially outperforming alternative functional forms. The three sigmoid parameters provide a compact representation that fully captures classification-relevant information, as demonstrated by equivalent classification performance using parameters only versus full profile features.

Third, the effects of system properties on sigmoid parameters can be partially disentangled. Noise level primarily determines amplitude and steepness, while curvature primarily determines midpoint. These effects are additive, with no significant interaction \citep{ward1963hierarchical}. The two factors together explain approximately 85\% of parameter variance.

\subsection{Interpretation of Parametric Structure}

The finding that a single component captures the majority of residual variance indicates that residual profiles vary along a single dimension corresponding to sigmoid amplitude \citep{stringer2019high}. The consistency of this finding across systems suggests that residual dimensionality profiles exhibit a stereotyped shape determined primarily by amplitude.

The sigmoid parameterization provides a decomposition of this one-dimensional variation into interpretable components \citep{hotz2023intrinsic}. Amplitude $A$ reflects the saturation level of residual dimensionality. Midpoint $k_0$ reflects the neighborhood scale at which half the residual dimensionality is revealed. Steepness $\beta$ reflects the rate of transition from low to high residual dimensionality.

The superiority of the sigmoid form over logarithmic and power-law alternatives suggests that residual dimensionality reflects a saturating accumulation process with a characteristic transition scale.

The cluster structure (Sparse separating from all other systems) suggests that the sigmoid parameter space contains discrete regions corresponding to qualitatively different organizational principles \citep{gallego2017neural}. More recent theoretical perspectives suggest that observed dimensionality reflects an interplay between intrinsic constraints and task-relevant structure \citep{saxe2021if}.

\subsection{Methodological Implications}

These findings have implications for the application of multiscale dimensionality analysis. The sensitivity of sigmoid parameters to noise level indicates that residual analysis is sensitive to stochastic variation in data, potentially limiting reliability in empirical contexts where noise levels are high or variable \citep{coifman2006diffusion}. The finding that parameters remain robust at noise levels up to $\sigma = 0.2$ provides a reference point for acceptable noise levels.

The equivalence of sigmoid-only and full feature classification suggests that dimensionality profiling studies may benefit from reporting fitted sigmoid parameters rather than (or in addition to) raw dimensionality values \citep{paper3, paper4}. Parameters provide a more interpretable and compressed representation while preserving classification-relevant information.

The additive effects of noise and curvature indicate that factorial designs can separately estimate contributions from these sources, provided that appropriate controls are included.

\subsection{Limitations}

Multiple statistical tests were conducted across analyses. Reported p-values are uncorrected and should be interpreted in the context of convergent evidence across independent methods.

Confidence intervals for key estimates are reported where applicable; however, given the small number of systems and subjects, all inferential statistics should be interpreted with appropriate caution.

This study has several limitations. First, the empirical validation used a single fMRI dataset with a motor-task paradigm. The generalizability to other paradigms and imaging modalities remains to be established \citep{gao2017emergence}.

Second, the sample size (five systems) limits statistical power for some analyses. Classification accuracy estimates and cluster structure determinations would benefit from larger system samples to establish reliability.

Third, the null model construction relies on random matrix theory expectations for isotropic Gaussian data. Alternative null models might produce different residual structures, and the sensitivity of findings to null model choice was not systematically assessed \citep{marchenko1967distribution, couillet2011random}.

Fourth, the interpretation of parameter-property relationships is correlational rather than causal. While disentanglement analysis provides evidence for separable effects of noise and curvature, the specific causal mechanisms linking these properties to sigmoid parameters remain unspecified.

Fifth, only one dimensionality estimation method was examined. The $k$-NN variance method used here may not capture all aspects of multiscale dimensionality \citep{facco2017estimating}, and alternative estimators might produce different residual structures.

\subsection{Future Directions}

Several directions extend this work. Extension to other fMRI datasets and imaging modalities (MEG, ECoG, single-unit recordings) would further establish the generalizability of findings \citep{stringer2019high}.

Extension to additional system classes would clarify the scope of the findings. Theories of compressed sensing, sparse coding, and manifold learning predict specific dimensionality profile signatures that could be compared against the sigmoid parameterization identified here \citep{belkin2003laplacian, tenenbaum2000global}.

Alternative dimensionality estimators, including correlation-based methods, entropy-based methods, and graph-theoretic methods \citep{penzel2022spectral}, could be compared to assess the robustness of findings to estimator choice.

Investigation of temporal dynamics in residual structure would address how dimensionality profiles evolve over time, potentially revealing learning-related changes in representational geometry.

\section{Conclusion}

This work establishes that multiscale dimensionality profiles can be decomposed into generic and system-specific components, and that residual structure admits a low-dimensional parametric representation. These findings provide a foundation for interpreting dimensionality profiles in terms of underlying system properties and support the use of compact parametric models in empirical applications.

